et></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">N/CRM N/EEC N/ELX N/GEN N/NTO N/PLT R/EC R/EU R/FR R/WEU </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday FRENCH POLITICS FRENCH PRESIDENTIAL POLITICS ILLEGAL CAMPAIGN FUNDS POLTICAL CORRUPTION SB126955385469309739639045841179638698074461 Sarkozy, Nicolas Senussi, Abdullah Takieddine, Ziad SYND CODES_REVIEWED Europe News </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OEUN </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">World</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Former French President Nicolas Sarkozy Hits Back at His Accusers; Allegations he accepted illegal campaign cash are slanderous, former head of state tells national television</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>PARISâ€”Former French President Nicolas Sarkozy fired back against allegations that he accepted campaign cash from Moammar Gadhafi, saying the late Libyan dictator's family and associates had conspired to slander him after Mr. Sarkozy championed the military campaign that led to Gadhafi's downfall.</Para><Para>French authorities <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-brings-preliminary-charges-against-ex-president-sarkozy-1521665420?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=4">brought preliminary charges</ELink> Wednesday evening against Mr. Sarkozy for campaign-finance violations, corruption and accepting funds that had been diverted from Libya's public coffers. Judges restricted his travel and forbade him from communicating with other witnesses in the investigation. It was the first time such measures have been imposed on a former president in France's postwar era.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Speaking on prime-time television on Thursday, Mr. Sarkozy in an emotional interview said his accusers were lying and pledged to fight back.</Para><Para>"I am accused by people close to a dictator whose terrorist regime we destroyed," Mr. Sarkozy said. "There isn't the least proof."</Para><Para>As president, Mr. Sarkozy pushed the North Atlantic Treaty Organization to intervene in Libya against Gadhafi after he brutally cracked down on internal protests. The U.S., France, the U.K. and other NATO members conducted air strikes against Gadhafi's forces, ultimately helping rebel groups topple his regime.</Para><Para>Mr. Sarkozy suggested that the allegations against himâ€”made variously by Gadhafi's son, his brother-in-law, a Franco-Lebanese businessman close to the regime and othersâ€”were part of an effort to sabotage his political career. In April 2012, between the first and second round of the French election, the French website Mediapart reported on a Libyan document drafted in December 2006 that described a plan to funnel â‚¬50 million ($61.2 million) to Mr. Sarkozy's 2007 presidential election. At the time, Mr. Sarkozy was locked in a close contest with the Socialist FranÃ§ois Hollande, who would go on to defeat Mr. Sarkozy.</Para><Para>Another blow came in November 2016, as Mr. Sarkozy was vying to become the nominee of the center-right Les RÃ©publicains in the 2017 presidential election. Mediapart <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.mediapart.fr/en/journal/mot-cle/ziad-takieddine">published an interview</ELink> with Ziad Takieddine, a businessman and one-time associate of Mr. Sarkozy, who claimed that he delivered suitcases full of cash from Abdullah Senussi, Gadhafi's intelligence chief and brother-in-law, to the French Interior Ministry starting in late 2006, when Mr. Sarkozy held the office and was preparing his bid for the presidency.</Para><Para>On two occasions, Mr. Sarkozy himself saw Mr. Takieddine deliver the suitcases, Mr. Takieddine said.</Para><Para>The interview with Mr. Takieddine was published days before the first round of voting in the center-right primary, which knocked Mr. Sarkozy out of the race.</Para><Para>"The Mediapart document came out between the two rounds of the presidential election. The 'revelations' of the sinister Takieddine came out two days before the most important televised debate of the primary," Mr. Sarkozy said. "I can't let them do this."</Para><Para>On Thursday, Mr. Sarkozy was also asked about testimony from Mr. Senussi made to Libya's national prosecutor and provided to the International Criminal Court in The Hague in the Netherlands. According to French media, Mr. Senussi testified that he personally supervised payment of â‚¬5 million in cash to the Sarkozy campaignâ€”the same amount that Mr. Takieddine estimated he delivered in cash to the Interior Ministry.</Para><Para>Mr. Sarkozy retorted that Mr. Senussi was among six Libyans who were convicted by a French court of carrying out a terror attack on a French airliner in 1989.</Para><Para>"You have here a former president who has never been convicted," Mr. Sarkozy told his interviewer, "and you speak of a man who assassinated 170 people."</Para><Para>Write to Matthew Dalton at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:Matthew.Dalton@wsj.com">Matthew.Dalton@wsj.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Matthew Dalton </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-french-president-nicolas-sarkozy-hits-back-at-his-accusers-1521758509" type="webpage"></Item></Adoc